TY  - JOUR
T1  - Integrated and Decoupled Corporate Social Performance: Management Commitments, External Pressures, and Corporate Ethics Practices
AU  - Weaver, Gary R.
AU  - TreviÑo, Linda Klebe
AU  - Cochran, Philip L.
Y1  - 1999/10/01
PY  - 1999
DA  - 1999/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/256975
DO  - 10.5465/256975
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 539
EP  - 552
VL  - 42
IS  - 5
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Corporations can respond to expectations for socially responsible processes and outcomes in organizationally integrated ways or in easily decoupled fashion. This study focused on a particular type of socially responsible organizational process: formal corporate ethics programs. Theory suggests that external pressures for social performance encourage easily decoupled processes but that top management commitments can encourage both easily decoupled and integrated processes. Analysis of survey and archival data generally supported this position. Implications for social performance research, practice, and public policy are discussed.
AB  - Corporations can respond to expectations for socially responsible processes and outcomes in organizationally integrated ways or in easily decoupled fashion. This study focused on a particular type of socially responsible organizational process: formal corporate ethics programs. Theory suggests that external pressures for social performance encourage easily decoupled processes but that top management commitments can encourage both easily decoupled and integrated processes. Analysis of survey and archival data generally supported this position. Implications for social performance research, practice, and public policy are discussed.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/256975
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/256975
Y2  - 2026/04/24
